“Two decades ago there was mediocrity in schools and schools were populated with tutors that resulted in a culture of mediocrity which had nothing to do with innovation. Today this is totally changed. Schools have changed in that type of system that prevents pupils getting involved in routine things”, he pointed out.

Expert Stojanov also underlined the significance of creating a coordinated team of school directors, teachers and heads of municipalities.

“Coordinated actions among schools them haven’t been performing well so far, yet they proved to be successful in the towns the said officers had gathered”, he claimed.

Graduate of secondary school Vladimir Ivan, who deals with innovation in education, believes the implementation of e-learning systems makes noticeable improvement in a countrys economy, education and quality of living.

“It should be recognized that the networking as an element of the big reforms is a product for a long-term, and one school spent eight years in implementing this, having benefits for the pupils”, he said.

Yet, in the opinion of Sasa Vranjes, consultant for information technology at NDS, teachers need to be trained in the educational software, which leads to their better capacity and better results of pupils in public tests.
